05103nam a22011055i 9780520931121DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696803  a97805209311217 a10.1525/97805209311212doi  a(DE-B1597)520968  a(OCoLC)62865871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBV896.P19 4aBV896.P19 B58 2005eb 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a263/.0425694/090151 aBitton-Ashkelony, Brouria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEncountering the Sacred :bThe Debate on Christian Pilgrimage in Late Antiquity /cBrouria Bitton-Ashkelony. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (270 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage ;v3800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Basil of Caesarea’s and Gregory of Nyssa’s Attitudes toward Pilgrimage -- t2 Jerome’s Position on Pilgrimage -- t3 Augustine on Holy Space -- t4 Pilgrimage in Monastic Culture -- t5 Local versus Central Pilgrimage -- tBibliography -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Places -- tIndex of Biblical Citations0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis innovative study sheds new light on one of the most spectacular changes to occur in late antiquity—the rise of pilgrimage all over the Christian world—by setting the phenomenon against the wide background of the political and theological debates of the time. Asking how the emerging notion of a sacred geography challenged the leading intellectuals and ecclesiastical authorities, Brouria Bitton-Ashkelony deftly reshapes our understanding of early Christian mentalities by unraveling the process by which a territory of grace became a territory of power. Examining ancient writers' responses to the rising practice of pilgrimage, Bitton-Ashkelony offers a nuanced reading of their thinking on the merits and the demerits of pilgrimage, revealing theological and ecclesiastical motivations that have been overlooked, and questioning the long-held assumption of scholars that pilgrimage was only a popular, not an elite, religious practice. In addition to Greek and Latin sources, she includes Syriac material, which allows her to build a rich picture of the emerging theology of landscape that took shape over the fourth to sixth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian pilgrims and pilgrimageszPalestinexHistory of doctrinesyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aancient world.  aantiquity.  aaristocracy.  aaugustine.  abible.  achristian pilgrims.  achristian world.  achristianity.  aclass.  acloister.  aearly church.  aelite religion.  afolk religion.  agrace.  agregory of nyssa.  aholiness.  aholy land.  aholy men.  aholy sites.  aholy space.  ajerome.  ajerusalem.  alandscape.  amonasteries.  amonasticism.  amonks.  amonuments.  anonfiction.  anuns.  apalestine.  apilgrimage.  apilgrims.  apopular religion.  arelics.  areligion.  areligious devotion.  areligious practices.  asacred geography.  asacred space.  asaints.  atheology.  atombs.  atravel.  aworship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024191640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093112140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931121423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520931121/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-